# Markdown Style

## Document Structure

### Headings
- One H1 (`#`) per document — the document title
- Use H2 (`##`) for major sections, H3 (`###`) for subsections
- Don't skip levels (no H1 → H3 without H2)
- Use sentence case: "Getting started" not "Getting Started"
- No trailing punctuation in headings

### Organization
- Lead with the most important information (inverted pyramid)
- Start with a brief summary before diving into details
- Group related content under clear headings
- Keep sections focused; split long sections

## Text Formatting

### Inline Elements
- `backticks` for: code, filenames, paths, CLI commands, function names
- **Bold** for: UI elements, important warnings, key terms on first use
- *Italics* for: emphasis, introducing terms, titles of works
- Don't combine bold and italics unless absolutely necessary

### Line Width
- Wrap prose at 88 characters for consistency with code formatting
- No hard wrapping for tables or code blocks
- One sentence per line is acceptable for easier diffs

## Code Blocks

### Always Specify Language

```python
# Good: language specified
def example():
    pass
```

### Guidelines
- Keep examples minimal but complete (runnable when possible)
- Remove unnecessary comments unless they explain something non-obvious
- Use realistic variable names, not `foo`, `bar`, `baz`
- Show expected output in comments or separate block when helpful

### Inline Code
- Use for: `function_names()`, `variable_names`, `file.py`, `--flags`
- Don't use for: general emphasis (use bold/italics instead)
- Don't wrap entire sentences in backticks

## Lists

### When to Use
- Bullet lists: unordered items, features, options
- Numbered lists: sequential steps, ranked items, procedures
- Don't use lists for 1-2 items; write as prose instead

### Formatting
- Consistent punctuation: all items end with period, or none do
- Parallel structure: start each item the same way (verb, noun, etc.)
- Keep items concise; use sub-bullets sparingly
- Blank line before and after lists

## Links

### Style
- Prefer reference-style links for repeated or long URLs
- Use descriptive link text: [installation guide](url) not [click here](url)
- Relative links for internal docs: `[API docs](./api.md)`
- Absolute links for external resources

### Reference Links (for complex docs)

```markdown
See the [Python docs][python] and [Ruff][ruff] for more info.

[python]: https://docs.python.org/3/
[ruff]: https://docs.astral.sh/ruff/
```

## Tables

### When to Use
- Comparing options, features, or configurations
- Reference data with clear columns
- Don't use for simple key-value pairs (use a list instead)

### Formatting
- Align columns for readability in source
- Keep cells concise; link to details if needed
- Use `—` or `N/A` for empty cells, not blank

## README Structure

### Recommended Sections
1. **Title** + brief one-line description
2. **Overview**: 2-3 sentences on what it does and why
3. **Installation**: copy-paste commands
4. **Quick Start**: minimal working example
5. **Usage**: detailed examples (or link to docs)
6. **Configuration**: options, environment variables
7. **Contributing**: how to contribute (or link to CONTRIBUTING.md)
8. **License**: license type + link

### Keep It Scannable
- Use the first sentence of each section to summarize
- Put the most common use case first
- Link to detailed docs instead of duplicating content

## Callouts (GitHub-flavored)

```markdown
> [!NOTE]
> Useful information the reader should know.

> [!WARNING]
> Critical information about potential issues.

> [!TIP]
> Optional advice to help improve workflow.
```

## Collapsible Sections

```markdown
<details>
<summary>Click to expand</summary>

Hidden content goes here.

</details>
```

## Anti-Patterns

| Avoid | Use Instead |
|-------|-------------|
| "Click here" links | Descriptive link text |
| Walls of text | Headings, lists, whitespace |
| Screenshots of code | Actual code blocks |
| Multiple H1 headings | Single H1 for title only |
| `ALL CAPS` for emphasis | Bold or callout boxes |
| Excessive emoji | Sparingly, if at all |

## AI Directives

When generating or editing Markdown:
- Match the existing style and tone of the document
- Preserve existing heading hierarchy
- Don't add sections unless requested
- Keep edits minimal and focused
- Update table of contents if one exists
- Verify internal links still work after edits
